df.describe() is a Pandas function that provides summary statistics of a DataFrame. It calculates various quantiles, such as the count, mean, standard deviation, minimum, 25th percentile, 50th percentile (median), 75th percentile, and maximum values for each numerical column in the DataFrame. A detailed explanation of each feature is described below: \ count: The number of non-null values in each column. \ mean: The average value of each column. \ std: The standard deviation of each column. \ min: The minimum value of each column. \ 25%: The 25th percentile of each column. \ 50%: The 50th percentile (median) of each column.\ 75%: The 75th percentile of each column. \ max: The maximum value of each column.

Scatter Plots¶

Another way of performing EDA is by visualization using scatter plots. Scatter Plots are a type of graph used to visualize the relationship between two numerical variables. Each data point is represented by a dot on the graph, where the x-coordinate corresponds to the value of one variable and the y-coordinate corresponds to the value of the other variable. \ We are able to create these visualizations using the Matplotlib library and Seaborn library

In [ ]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

sns.scatterplot(x="median_income", y="median_house_value", data=df, color='orange')
plt.title("A Scatter Plot  of Median income against Median house values")
plt.show()

The key observations observed in this scatter plot are correlation and ceiling effect. \ Correlation: There seems to be a positive correlation between median income and median house value. As income increases, house values also tend to increase, though the relationship isn't perfectly linear. but it is almost linear. \ Ceiling Effect: The house values appear to be capped at 500,000 (a maximum threshold in the dataset). This ceiling effect results from a limit imposed in the dataset. I have preprocessed the data to filter out records with median_house_value = 500001 since it seems to be a cap for the median_house_value. \ Some of the insights on linear regression are: \ Based on the scatter plot, a linear regression analysis could provide valuable insights into the relationship between median income and median house values. There appears to be a positive correlation between median income and median house values, suggesting that as median income increases, median house values tend to increase as well.

In [ ]:
housing_preprocessed = df[df.median_house_value != 500001]
sns.scatterplot(x="median_income", y="median_house_value", data=housing_preprocessed, color='orange')
plt.title("A Scatter Plot  of Median income against Median house values")
plt.show()
In [ ]:
sns.scatterplot(x="population", y="median_house_value", data=df, color='green')
plt.title("A Scatter Plot  of Median income against Population")
plt.show()

Some of the observations noted here are as follows: \ There is no clear linear correlation between population and median house value. The majority of house values are distributed similarly across various population sizes, especially for populations under 5,000. \ Most house values are capped at $500,000, indicating the same ceiling effect we noticed earlier. This will be dealt with and a new scatter plot will be plotted below \ The population values are heavily clustered under 10,000. As we move beyond 10,000, we see fewer data points, and those that exist seem to show no specific trend in house prices. \ Some of the insights for Linear Regression are: \ Weak Predictive Power: A linear regression model using population as a predictor for median house value may show low predictive power. The scatter plot indicates a weak or almost nonexistent relationship. \ Outliers: The few outliers at very large population sizes (above 30,000) might skew the results of any regression analysis.

In [ ]:
sns.scatterplot(x="households", y="median_house_value", data=df, color='blue')
plt.title("A Scatter Plot  of Median income against Number of households")
plt.show()

Some of the observations here are as follows: A large portion of data points are between 0 and 2000 households. The spread of the house values increases as the number of households increases. At lower household counts, the points are tightly packed with some outliers, while at higher household counts, the points are more spread out. \ There appears to be a visible boundary at a median house value of 500,000. This was as a result of a cap in house values, possibly due to data truncation. This will be dealt with and a new scatter plot will be plotted below. The pattern of points suggests that the relationship between households and median house value may not be perfectly linear. For smaller household counts, the increase in house values is not directly proportional to the increase in households. \ Some of the insights for Linear Regression are: \ Non-linearity: The scatter plot suggests that the relationship between the number of households and the median house value is not strictly linear. Especially at lower household numbers (0-2000), house values increase quickly and then the spread widens, which could violate the linearity assumption of linear regression. Thus, a simple linear regression might not fully capture the relationship.\ Therefore, While linear regression is the first step, given the spread and clustering in the data, exploring non-linear regression techniques (like polynomial regression or decision trees) might yield better results but we wont handle that now.

Based on the above, describe the 4 variables used in this lab. Observations such as their meaning, range and additional characteristics that you notice. This should be concise, and relevant (1 point).

MedianHousevalue: Median house value for households within a block (measured in US Dollars). This is the dependent variable we're focusing on for predicting housing prices. It ranges from $14,999 to $500,001 (due to a capping at 500,001) and its Mean is $206,856. The distribution is likely skewed, with many data points closer to the lower and middle house price ranges and a smaller number near the upper cap. \ medianIncome: Median income for households within a block of houses (measured in tens of thousands of US Dollars). It ranges from 0.4999 (possibly an outlier or data entry error) to 15.0001 and its Mean is 3.87 (roughly $38,700 when considering income in units of tens of thousands). A major characteristic of this feature is that has a strong correlation with house value prices. \ Population: Total number of people residing within a block. It ranges from 3(indicating very small block groups or potential data entry issues) to 35,682 and its Mean is 1,425. An observation here is that The population ranges dramatically, from as few as 3 people to over 35,000. This could suggest the inclusion of both urban and rural block groups. \ households: Total number of households, a group of people residing within a home unit, for a block. It ranges from 1 to 6,082 and its Mean is 499. Similar to population, this feature displays considerable variation, which could indicate different urban, suburban, and rural characteristics across block groups.

Running the three linear regressions (fitting)¶

In [ ]:
from sklearn import linear_model
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error
In [ ]:
#Running a Linear Regression to predict my dependent variable(median_house_value) from my independent variable(median_income)
train_size = int(len(housing_preprocessed) * 0.8)
train = housing_preprocessed[:train_size]
test = housing_preprocessed[train_size:]

sns.scatterplot(x="median_income", y="median_house_value", data=train, color="blue")
sns.scatterplot(x="median_income", y="median_house_value", data=test, color="red")
Out[ ]:
<Axes: xlabel='median_income', ylabel='median_house_value'>
In [ ]:
model1 = linear_model.LinearRegression()
model1.fit(X=train[["median_income"]], y=train[["median_house_value"]])
Out[ ]:
LinearRegression()

In [ ]:
# plot the regression line against the training data
sns.scatterplot(x="median_income", y="median_house_value", data=train, color="blue")
plt.plot(train[["median_income"]], model1.predict(train[["median_income"]]), color="black", linewidth=3)
sns.set_style("darkgrid")
plt.show()
In [ ]:
# print coefficients
intercept1 = model1.intercept_
coef1 = model1.coef_
print("Intercept:", intercept1)
print("Coefficients:" ,coef1)

# print the MSE and MAE on the test set
mse_value1 = mean_squared_error(test[['median_house_value']], model1.predict(test[['median_income']]))
print("Mean squared error:", mse_value1)

mae_value1 = mean_absolute_error(test[['median_house_value']], model1.predict(test[['median_income']]))
print("Mean Absolute error:", mae_value1)

Summary¶

Model 1 appears to be the best-performing model based on the given metrics. It has the lowest MAE and MSE, suggesting that it provides more accurate predictions. However, further analysis, including examining the coefficients, and evaluating the model's performance on new data, is recommended to gain a more comprehensive understanding of its effectiveness. \ In Model 1 The coefficient is significantly larger than in other models, indicating a strong relationship between the predictor and the target variable. In Model 2 and Model 3, the coefficients are smaller, suggesting a weaker relationship. \ Based on MAE and MSE, Model 1 has the best goodness-of-fit. It has the lowest MAE and MSE, suggesting that its predictions are closer to the actual values on average.
